{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489187"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:08:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:08:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"611"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582682"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:51:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:51:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"611"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/611"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.01,0.58,0.21,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"611"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112742"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/611"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"611"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94776"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5364"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6062"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6335"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14755"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15014"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15660"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32581"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34247"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43803"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46348"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112742","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112742"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 37-year-old man presents for a health check for insurance purposes. He does not have any current health issues, his medical history is unremarkable and he does not take any medications. His father developed bowel cancer at the age of 47 and two paternal uncles had the same disease at the age of 59 and 64. This patient needs to be given some advice with respect to screening for bowel cancer. The place of faecal immunochemical testing (iFOBT) and colonoscopy is discussed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most appropriate screening plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Biennial iFOBT starting at age 45","Biennial iFOBT starting at age 50","Five-yearly colonoscopy starting now","Five-yearly colonoscopy starting aged 40","Annual colonoscopy starting aged 45"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EScreening recommendations are based on the lifetime risk of colorectal cancer (CRC) and should be determined by the number and type of relatives affected by CRC as well as their age of diagnosis. Screening recommendations for the general public include a biennial faecal occult blood test (FOBT) which can reduce CRC mortality by 16%. Colonoscopy is not recommended as a screening tool for the general population as there is indirect and direct harm associated with the procedure that does not necessarily outweigh the benefits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECurrently, there are three levels of risk stratification for CRC which have been developed by the NHMRC to guide screening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 1 - similar risk as the general population\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic people with no family history of colorectal cancer OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne 1st-degree relative with CRC \u226560 years\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: FOBT should be completed every 2 years from 45 years old as per usual screening protocol. Colonoscopy is generally not recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 2 - moderately increased risk\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic people with one 1st-degree relative CRC diagnosed \u0026lt;60 years OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo 1st-degree relatives with CRC at any age or one 1st-degree and one or more 2nd-degree relatives diagnosed at any age\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: Colonoscopy should be offered 5 yearly starting at \u003Cstrong\u003E10 years younger\u003C/strong\u003E than the earliest diagnosis of CRC in a 1st-degree relative, or age \u003Cstrong\u003E50 \u003C/strong\u003E(whichever is earliest).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 3 - high risk, excluding hereditary cancer syndromes\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic with two 1st-degree and one 2nd-degree relative with colorectal cancer, with at least one diagnosed before 50 years old OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo 1st-degree relatives and two or more 2nd-degree relatives diagnosed with CRC at any age OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThree or more 1st-degree relatives with CRC at any age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: refer to the familial cancer clinic for genetic assessment before a screening decision is made if Lynch syndrome has not been excluded. If Lynch syndrome is excluded, colonoscopy should be offered every 5 years starting at \u003Cstrong\u003E10 years younger\u003C/strong\u003E than the earliest age of diagnosis of colorectal cancer in a first-degree relative or age \u003Cstrong\u003E40 \u003C/strong\u003Eyears (whichever is earliest)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn terms of risk stratification, this patient belongs to category 2 (one 1st-degree relative diagnosed with bowel cancer before the age of 60, two 2nd-degree relatives diagnosed at any age). Based on this,\u003Cstrong\u003E\u00a0he should undergo screening with a colonoscopy now, at the age of 37 (10 years before his father\u0027s CRC diagnosis), then every 5 years.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommencing in September 2023, there are new recommendations to commence iFOBT screening for the general population (category 1 patients) biennially from age 45 years, rather than 50 years. Given that the patient is in category two,\u003Cstrong\u003E options that involve screening patients biennially from 45 and 50 years old are incorrect.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough more frequent colonoscopy screening may be indicated for certain high risk groups (e.g. Lynch syndrome, ulcerative colitis with primary sclerosing cholangitis), \u003Cstrong\u003Eannual screening with a colonoscopy \u003C/strong\u003Eis not appropriate for this patient\u003Cstrong\u003E.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELastly, screening the patient \u003Cstrong\u003Efive-yearly with a colonoscopy starting from the age of 40 is an incorrect answer,\u003C/strong\u003E as category two patients are recommended to commence screening 10 years before their relative\u0027s first CRC diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Colonoscopy starting 10 years before the diagnosis of 1st-degree relative is recommended for patients at moderate risk (category two) of colorectal cancer.","Colorectal cancer risk stratification takes into account the number of 1st- and 2nd-degree relatives affected and their age of diagnosis"],"references":["RACGP. Guidance for preventative activities in general practice. (2024 Jun 28) Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/8f57912d-11bd-47c9-9d24-81a2301e9fe2/Guidelines-for-preventive-activities-in-general-practice.aspx","Cancer Council Australia. Clinical practice guidelines for the prevention, early detection and management of colorectal cancer: Risk and screening based on family history. 2024. Available at: https://app.magicapp.org/#/guideline/jz5DdE","Markey W, Srinath H. The alarming rise of early-onset  colorectal cancer. Aust J Gen Pract. 2025; 54:392-99."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94776"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"611"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94776"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-05T09:06:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-05T09:07:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"611"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112742"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadi